<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUTTING WATER USE AND DWP LEAKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I would like to register my outrage at the way the new storm drain levy 
schedule was calculated by the Los Angeles City Council (Aug. 1). Once again, 
people who reside on large lot residential properties have been unfairly 
singled out. 
</P>
<P>
Isn't the sewer fee devised by the DWP bad enough? 
</P>
<P>
The additional water used on our property goes into the ground, not into the 
storm drains and certainly not into the sewers. Our trees, roses and other 
shrubs (no pool) help the environment of this increasingly crowded, asphalted 
and polluted city. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, what makes this entire situation so infuriating is that this same group 
of geniuses (otherwise known as the City Council) just approved the paving of 
the hills of Porter Ranch with 4,000 new homes and office buildings. No doubt 
Councilman Hal Bernson will probably tell us that this grotesque project will 
have little impact on the storm drains just like it isn't going to impact the 
sewers, freeways, air and landfills. Sure, Hal. 
</P>
<P>
LOREN ZELDIN 
</P>
<P>
Reseda 
</P>
</TEXT>
