<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIE REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
'AIR AMERICA' STALLS IN FINDING ITS FOCUS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PETER RAINER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It used to be said that Vietnam was the great undeclared war both in real life 
and on the screen. Until the last decade or so, the war was virtually absent 
from our screens. Now, of course, it's rare that a month goes by without some 
Vietnam-themed feature or television movie. While the general run of such films 
is of a rather high quality, the themes and subject matter have become 
repetitive. 
</P>
<P>
That's one reason why "Air America," (citywide) which stars Mel Gibson and 
Robert Downey and is about the CIA's secret airline operating in Laos in 1969, 
seems so invigorating at first. It's a great, untapped movie subject, and the 
director Roger Spottiswoode works up the material in high style. At its best 
it's a luxuriant black comedy. The buccaneer aviators who maneuver the 
experimental prop planes and huge, lumbering transports above the lush Laotian 
highlands are juiced by their own adrenalin. They're all a little high, and the 
movie itself has a slightly delirious, narcotized quality. 
</P>
<P>
The black comedy arises naturally out of the material. The CIA kept a secret 
mercenary anti-communist army in Laos for more than a decade, and Air America 
was its air support. As a covert, CIA-run, civilian-operated airline in charge 
of transporting everything from pigs to opium, Air America did not even 
officially exist. The pilots, recruited both from civilian life and from the 
military, were generally not told about the nature of their missions, or even 
that they were working for the CIA. (That doesn't mean they didn't know.) But, 
if the dangers were extraordinary -- more Air America pilots died in Laos than 
in Cambodia or Vietnam -- so were the financial rewards. Pilots got paid by the 
flight, and often there were dozens per day. 
</P>
<P>
The wacky disassociation of working for a non-existent airline in a 
non-existent war is what gives "Air America" its tone of funhouse grisliness. 
(The film opens with Nixon on TV telling the world there is no American 
presence in Laos.) These non-people don't even have the solace of having their 
heroism recognized. Their exploits, like their deaths, go officially 
unrecorded. 
</P>
<P>
As long as the film is racking up its absurdist points, it's a free-wheeling, 
sporty entertainment. The shots of huge porkers being parachuted to earth in 
crates, of Buddhist priests blessing the planes before lift-off, or the sight 
of a miniature golf course carved out of the jungle, have a special kind of 
comic charge. They reflect what really happened in Laos. The absurdity isn't 
tacked on to the story; it is the story. And there are moments when the 
nuttiness has a majestic sweep, as when a storm-tossed plane emerges from dark 
clouds and into the huge, looming face of a Buddhist shrine. 
</P>
<P>
As the film floats along, however, it remains essentially without focus. 
There's a conflict built into the script all right: Gene Ryack (Mel Gibson), a 
veteran of 15 years flying in Southeast Asia, tries to live down the guilt of 
transporting opium as a routine part of his job. Billy Covington (Robert 
Downey, Jr.), recruited from L.A. after botching his job as an eye-in-the-sky 
air traffic pilot, arrives in Laos with only the most naive assumptions about 
his job. When he discovers the extent of the corruption, he goes in for some 
free-style sabotage and, in the process, forces Gene into a moral reckoning. 
</P>
<P>
But the conflict is a case of too little too late and, in any event, it seems 
de-fanged. Robert Downey, Jr. gives a wonderfully open and engaging performance 
but, the way the film has been set up, his arrant innocence seems like a plot 
convenience. It's true that the Air Americans were kept in the dark about a 
great many things, but, with a mentor like Gene, who is so supremely cynical 
that he can't say anything to anyone without smirking, Billy seems not so much 
callow as dumb. 
</P>
<P>
"Air America" has a political consciousness: the battle sequences have gravity 
and the shots of the Laotian peasants are stunningly empathetic. The film 
exhibits a healthy "MASH"-like disrespect for the dangerous baloney of 
officialese. But the "48 HRS"-style buddy-buddy badinage and rough-housing 
between the aviators doesn't fill out the film's visual grandeur. It diminishes 
it. (So do the numerous what-the-hell anachronisms, like references to Mother 
Teresa and General Ky's liquor store in Orange County. In 1969!) 
</P>
<P>
Mel Gibson gives a cocky, assured performance -- a star performance. But he 
doesn't provide the kind of shadowings that might make Gene's guilt-ridden 
con-artistry resonate. Or maybe the shadings were edited out. There's so much 
voluminous detail and incident in "Air America" that at times the film 
resembles a vast swatch of footage; you get the feeling 10 other movies could 
have been made from what was shot. Some of the characters, like Burt Kwouk's 
deliciously corrupt General Lu Soong, are given ample display; others, like 
Nancy Travis' refugee camp coordinator, are barely in the movie, even though 
their roles seemed conceived on a much fuller scale. 
</P>
<P>
It's possible that the filmmakers got so high on the exhilarating possibilities 
in the material that they just let the cameras run, waiting for it to all come 
together in the editing room. "Air America" is far from a disgrace, but it's so 
rare to see a film with this much panoramic verve that you want it to deliver 
the real goods and not this cargo-load of tinkertoy war-is-heck ironies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, AIR LIFT: Mel Gibson, left, and Robert Downey Jr. star in "Air 
America," a high-flying black comedy that finds its focus too late. Reviewed by 
Peter Rainer. F8 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
