<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: REMAINS IDENTIFIED AS LONG BEACH WOMAN'S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The remains of a woman discovered by hikers near Roseburg, Ore., have been 
identified through dental records as those of a Long Beach resident who 
vanished almost two years ago, authorities said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
The remains, found by hikers May 31 on private forest land 30 miles southeast 
of Roseburg, were identified as those of Estella D. Vaughan, 46, who was 
reported missing from the Long Beach area in October, 1988, said Detective Joe 
Perkins of the Douglas County major crimes unit. He said the case is being 
treated as a homicide. 
</P>
<P>
The identification of the woman also involved a nationwide computer search, 
Perkins said. Police had asked for the public's help in determining the woman's 
whereabouts before her death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
