<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK; 
</P>
<P>
NEW MAINTENANCE BUILDINGS PLANNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a first step to reduce human impact on Yosemite Valley, the National Park 
Service is planning to tear down a score of maintenance buildings and construct 
new ones in El Portal at the park's western edge. 
</P>
<P>
National Park Service Director James Ridenour said $16 million to make the move 
is budgeted for 1992. Under a master plan developed for the park, most motor 
vehicle traffic would eventually be barred from the valley. Shuttle buses would 
carry more than 3 million visitors a year to and from the 7-mile-long, 
1-mile-wide area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
