<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
EUREKA; 
</P>
<P>
SPIKES IN 3 TREE LOGS DISCOVERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seven 10-inch spikes were found in three Douglas fir logs prepared for sawing 
at Louisiana-Pacific's mill in Samoa, the lumber company reported. 
</P>
<P>
"It's fortunate nobody was hurt," the firm's division manager, Joe Wheeler, 
said. The spikes were discovered on Aug. 2. It was the first reported incident 
of tree "spiking" in about two years. The tactic -- favored by opponents of 
old-growth logging -- has been renounced by sponsors of Redwood Summer, Earth 
First! Wheeler called on leaders of the groups to again disavow spiking to 
prevent injuries to workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
