<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
STATE TO CONFISCATE RANCH TABLE GRAPES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State agriculture officials said they will confiscate all table grapes grown on 
seven acres of a Delano ranch on grounds that they were sprayed illegally for 
the second consecutive year. During a recent Department of Food and Agriculture 
hearing, Sandrini Bros. growers contended that there was a laboratory error or 
a vendetta by the department's staff. 
</P>
<P>
However, a hearing officer found in favor of the department's proposal to 
confiscate the fruit, spokeswoman Veda Federighi said. Department Director 
Henry Voss upheld the hearing officer's decision. There was no immediate word 
whether Sandrini Bros. will appeal to Kern County Superior Court. The state 
contends that tests showed traces on Sandrini's grapes of a growth regulator 
called Fix, technically known as 4-CPA, which is registered only for tomatoes, 
Federighi said. Sandrini also was charged with using Fix last year, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
