<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAPANESE CHEMICAL MAKER, SHELL TO SET UP JOINT VENTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mitsui Toatsu Chemicals, Inc., a major Japanese chemical maker, said it will 
establish an equally owned venture with Shell International Chemical Co. of 
Britain to make polyurethane resin raw materials. 
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo-based company said a production base will be established in Spain, 
Italy or France. 
</P>
<P>
The two companies are scheduled to complete a joint feasibility study in the 
three countries by the end of this year and the site of a plant will be chosen 
early next year. 
</P>
<P>
Mitsui said plans call for building a factory that would have annual production 
capacity of 50,000 tons of diphenyl methane diisocyanate (MDI), raw materials 
for polyurethane resin. 
</P>
<P>
Demand for MDI is growing sharply because of its widespread application in 
areas including household electric appliances and automotive parts, the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
World MDI production was estimated at 1.3 million tons last year, the company 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
