<HEADLINE>
<P>
BARYSHNIKOV TO TOUR WITH NEW COMPANY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PETER CATALANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mikhail Baryshnikov, who dances the choreography of Mark Morris with a series 
of engagements in 18 cities in the Midwest and South this fall, will skip the 
major metropolitan cities in his new company's inaugural season. 
</P>
<P>
Christina Sterner, spokeswoman for Baryshnikov Productions, the producer of the 
tour, said the 42-year-old dancer will be joined by seven other dancers from 
around the country as part of the White Oak Dance Project that starts in Oct. 
24 and continues through mid-November. The tour will wind its way through Ohio, 
Florida and other parts of the South. 
</P>
<P>
According to Sterner, the White Oak Dance Project was conceived as an "outlet 
to give people across the country an access to the work of Mark Morris, which 
is the important thing." Morris, 33, will not tour with the company. If the 
tour is successful, Sterner said the White Oak Dance Project will visit the 
major metropolitan areas in the spring of 1991. 
</P>
<P>
Currently Morris and the dancers for the White Oak Dance Project, including 
Baryshnikov, are secluded at the White Oak Plantation, in Yulee, Fla., near 
Jacksonville. Their sponsor is the philanthropist, Howard Gilman, who is 
assisting Baryshnikov Productions in booking and promoting the tour. 
</P>
<P>
"It was Misha and Howard's vision to produce this tour across the country, but 
Howard's main contribution has been in providing the environment for the 
artistic process at this point," said Sterner. 
</P>
<P>
None of the principals have made themselves available to the press. "They're 
very much in the artistic process. That's where the focus is right now," 
Sterner said. 
</P>
<P>
All the dancers will remain in Yulee until the end of August, when Morris and 
his Monnaie Dance Group, which is based in Brussels, will begin touring the 
United States and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
Morris is due in Los Angeles Sept. 3 to address the Dance Critics Assn. 
conference at Cal State Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Morris ; Photo, Baryshnikov 
</P>
